[11] Japan: Narita airport
Date: Wed 1 May 2019
Source: Japan Today [abridged, edited]
https://japantoday.com/category/national/2-narita-airport-workers-confirmed-as-having-measles


Two workers at Narita airport are confirmed to have been infected with measles, the local government said Tue [30 Apr 2019], warning about the risk of possible exposure to the highly contagious virus at one of the busiest airports in Japan.

The local government of Chiba Prefecture, where the airport is located, said a male worker in his 30s fell ill with a fever of 39 C [102 F] on Tue 30 Apr 2019 last week.

Another worker, a teenage woman, became sick on 20 Apr 2019 but did not go into work and is not believed to have spread the virus.

Japan was declared measles-free by the World Health Organization in 2015, but over 200 cases of infection have been reported this year [2019] after an outbreak of the disease in Okinawa Prefecture and some other regions last year [2018].

Medical experts say infections increased in line with a surge in foreign tourists.

Narita International Airport employs about 43 000 people and services approximately 118 000 customers daily. The airport had been experiencing a rush of travelers flying overseas ahead of the 10-day Golden Week holiday.

