[16] Measles: Increasing Vaccine Uptake Correlates With Decreasing Disease Rates - Background
Source: GIDEON (Global Infectious Disease Epidemiology Network) [edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=10c8833a-4ceb64e1-10ca7a0f-0cc47aa8c6e0-d34b947f4c9ddfea&u=https://www.gideononline.com/2019/05/02/measles-correlation-of-vaccine-uptake-with-disease-rates/


The following is a country-by-country analysis of measles reporting trends vs. vaccine uptake. For purposes of consistency, incidence data and population statistics used to calculate rates per 100 000 are limited to those published by the World Health Organization (WHO). Resultant graphs were generated by Gideon and abstracted from the Gideon e-book series [1,2]. Estimates of true vaccination update are those published by WHO, in most cases available only since 1980. Data published by the countries themselves were not used, to avoid possible bias or inconsistency when comparing data among countries. Historical disease data which precede 1980 have been appended to graphs to further appreciate the impact of vaccination.

See A-to-Z 135 individual country graphs at
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=10c8833a-4ceb64e1-10ca7a0f-0cc47aa8c6e0-d34b947f4c9ddfea&u=https://www.gideononline.com/2019/05/02/measles-correlation-of-vaccine-uptake-with-disease-rates/.

The reader will note that in virtually all cases, the presumed impact of vaccine uptake on disease incidence occurs when vaccine uptake exceeds 80%, and again when rates increase beyond 90%. As such, the few countries which have not achieved 80% uptake, or have consistently reported over 90% uptake since 1980 are excluded. Graphs are not included for countries for which data are not reported or reported only sporadically.

Individual graphs for 135 countries are presented in alphabetical order. In 127 (94%) of these, a clear relationship seems to exist between increasing vaccine uptake and decreasing rates of measles. In 8 cases, temporary "spikes" in disease incidence were reported during years of high vaccine uptake: Japan, Jordan, Republic of Korea, Seychelles, Solomon Islands, South Africa, Sri Lanka and Syria.

I have not attempted to perform a statistical analysis of this phenomenon and cannot say with certainty that a confounding (3rd) factor does not exist. Nevertheless, these graphs appear to indicate a favorable effect of vaccination on measles incidence.

References:
1. Gideon e-Gideon multi-graph tool, https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=39bd8da2-659e6a79-39bf7497-0cc47aa8c6e0-7f49d41ce8ecca0e&u=https://www.gideononline.com/cases/multi-graphs/

2. Berger S. Measles: Global Status, 2019. 548 pages , 538 graphs , 5779 references. Gideon e-books,
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=94d08969-c8f36eb2-94d2705c-0cc47aa8c6e0-3ebf518b5664dad6&u=https://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/disease/measles-global-status/

--
Communicated by:
Prof. Steve Berger
